\begin_layout Standard
For diagram b in Fig1, the contribution is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Gamma_{b}^{+}=\int\cancel{k}\gamma_{5}\widetilde{F}^{2}(k)\frac{1}{D_{\phi}(k)}\frac{\cancel{p'}-\cancel{k}+m_{N}}{D_{B}(p'-k)}\gamma^{+}\frac{\cancel{p}-\cancel{k}+m_{N}}{D_{B}(p-k)}\cancel{k}\gamma_{5}\delta(y-\frac{k^{+}}{P^{+}})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I do the same separate in diagram i case.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 part is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
A_{b} & =\text{\ensuremath{\int(\Lambda^{2}-m_{\phi}^{2})^{4}\frac{\textrm{Tr}[\cancel{k}\gamma_{5}(\cancel{p'}-\cancel{k}+m_{N})\gamma^{+}(\cancel{p}-\cancel{k}+m_{N})\cancel{k}\gamma_{5}]}{D_{\Lambda}^{4}(k)D_{\phi}(k)D_{B}(p'-k)D_{B}(p-k)}}}\delta(y-\frac{k^{+}}{P^{+}})\\
 & =\int\frac{d^{4}k}{(2\pi)^{4}}(\frac{b_{1}}{D_{\Lambda}^{4}(k)D_{\phi}(k)D_{B}(p'-k)D_{B}(p-k)}+\frac{b_{2}}{D_{\phi}(k)D_{\Lambda}^{4}(k)})\delta(y-\frac{k^{+}}{P^{+}})
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then first term is normal integral which can be calculated with residue
 theorem and the second term is 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 term.
 The normal part can be expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline*}
\int\frac{d^{4}k}{(2\pi)^{4}}\frac{b_{1}}{D_{\Lambda}^{4}(k)D_{\phi}(k)D_{B}(p'-k)D_{B}(p-k)}\delta(y-\frac{k^{+}}{P^{+}})\\
=\int\frac{d^{4}k}{(2\pi)^{4}}(\frac{b'_{1}k^{-}}{D_{\Lambda}^{4}(k)D_{\phi}(k)D_{B}(p'-k)D_{B}(p-k)}+\frac{b_{1}''}{D_{\Lambda}^{4}(k)D_{\phi}(k)D_{B}(p'-k)D_{B}(p-k)})\delta(y-\frac{k^{+}}{P^{+}})
\end{multline*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This week, I check the integral above.
 The integral should have no issue and the contribution of diagram b can
 be calculated using the similar method as diagram i.
 Last week I made a mistake in my program.
 The splitting function can be expressed as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f & =f_{1}+f_{2}+f_{\delta}\delta(y)\\
g & =g_{1}+g_{2}+g_{\delta}\delta(y)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
the 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}+f_{2}$
\end_inset

 means the normal part of the splitting function which is separated in 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{+}=(1-\xi)P^{+}$
\end_inset

 due to the singularity comes from 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{B}(p'-k)=(p'-k)^{2}-M^{2}+i\epsilon$
\end_inset

 change it's position from upside to the down side of the axis and the 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\delta}\delta(y+\xi)$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 term.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The splitting function should satisfy that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{-\xi}^{1}dyf(y)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{-\xi}^{1}dyg(y)$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 independent.
 For diagram b, the result is, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=0.1,0.2$
\end_inset

, ignore some coefficient
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{-\xi}^{1-2\xi}dyf_{1}(y)+\int_{1-2\xi}^{1}dyf_{2}(y)+f_{\delta}=7.27795
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{-\xi}^{1-2\xi}dyg_{1}(y)+\int_{1-2\xi}^{1}dyg_{2}(y)+g_{\delta}=-6.566548599
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

