\begin_layout Standard
For diagram d and e, the KR diagram with normal vertex.
 The calculation is finished and the result is checked by compare the integral
 with the form factor result.
 The contribution from these diagrams is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Gamma_{(d+e)}^{+}=\int F(k)^{2}\frac{i}{D_{\phi}(k)}(\cancel{k}\gamma_{5}\frac{\cancel{p'}-\cancel{k}+M_{B}}{D_{B}(p'-k)}\gamma^{\mu}\gamma_{5}+\gamma^{\mu}\gamma_{5}\frac{\cancel{p}-\cancel{k}+M_{B}}{D_{B}(p-k)}\cancel{k}\gamma_{5})\delta(y-\frac{k^{+}}{P^{+}})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The result is separated into two part
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f & =f_{res}+\delta f\\
g & =g_{res}+\delta g
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The lowest moment of splitting function should be equal to the form factor
 calculation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
F(q)*\int dy(f_{res}+\delta f) & =F_{1}\\
F(q)*\int dy(g_{res}+\delta g) & =F_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And when 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}=1MeV^{2}$
\end_inset

 the integral is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int dy(f_{res}+\delta f) & =0.0696379\\
F_{1} & =0.0174106\\
F(q) & =\frac{1}{4}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 part should be 0, but the result from splitting function is not very small,
 
