\begin_inset Formula $\xi=0$
\end_inset

 like diagram b.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For diagram f and g, the additional KR diagram from nonlocal Lagrangian.
 The contribution can be expressed as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Gamma_{(f+g)}^{+} & =\int\frac{d^{4}k}{(2\pi)^{4}}\frac{i}{D_{\phi}(k)}\tilde{F}(k)[\frac{2k^{+}-q^{+}}{2kq-q^{2}}(\tilde{F}(k)-\tilde{F}(k-q))\cancel{k}\gamma_{5}\frac{\cancel{p'}-\cancel{k}+M_{B}}{D_{B}(p'-k)}(\cancel{k}-\cancel{q})\gamma_{5}\\
 & +\frac{2k^{+}+q^{+}}{2kq+q^{2}}(\tilde{F}(k+q)-\tilde{F}(k))(\cancel{k}+\cancel{q})\gamma_{5}\frac{\cancel{p}-\cancel{k}+M_{B}}{D_{B}(p-k)}\cancel{k}\gamma_{5}]\delta(y-\frac{k^{+}}{P^{+}})
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The splitting function still is separated to two part.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f & =f_{res}+\delta f\\
g & =g_{res}+\delta g
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These two diagrams have same 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 term 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\delta f & =-2.6351\delta(y)\\
\delta g & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The normal integral is different from other cases.
 The lowest moment of splitting function from single diagram is 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 dependent and two result are different.
 In the normal KR diagram, the result is same no matter the position of
 the vertex.
 The lowest moment of the normal part splitting function from diagram f
 is listed below with 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=0.1\ Q^{2}=1GeV^{2}$
\end_inset

 ignoring some coefficient
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int dyf_{f} & =3.614491865\;\xi=0.1\\
\int dyf_{f} & =4.121612607\;\xi=0.2
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And for diagram g the result is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int dyf_{g} & =2.600249573\;\xi=0.1\\
\int dyf_{g} & =2.093126056\;\xi=0.2
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The result of these two diagram is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int dyf & =\int dy(f_{f}+f_{g})\\
 & =6.21474\;\xi=0.1\\
 & =6.21474\;\xi=0.2
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 part, the result is same.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int dyg_{f} & =1.890929104\;\xi=0.1\\
\int dyg_{f} & =1.383799830\;\xi=0.2
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int dyg_{g} & =2.905187580\;\xi=0.1\\
\int dyg_{g} & =3.412314403\;\xi=0.2
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int dyg & =\int dy(g_{f}+g_{g})\\
 & =4.79612\;\xi=0.1\\
 & =4.79611\;\xi=0.2
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And compared with the form factor result, we should have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\tilde{F}(q)\int dyf & =F_{1}\\
\tilde{F}(q)\int dyg & =F_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the other diagram like diagram d and e, the normal KR diagrams, the equation
 is satisfied even if only one diagram's contribution considered.
 But for diagram f and g, the additional KR diagrams, we must consider two
 diagram's contribution together.
 With 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=0.1\ Q^{2}=1GeV^{2}$
\end_inset

, the form factor should be
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\tilde{F}(q)\int dyf & =0.00695274\\
\tilde{F}(q)\int dyg & =0.0353042
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While the form factor result from previous work is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
F_{1} & =0.00695275\\
F_{2} & =0.0353042
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

